Clearly not. The creature was content to whistle and attempted to charge straight at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite its size, it was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help but scream when she almost lost her grip on its too smooth scales.
"HOW DO YOU KILL THEM?", Nyssi shouted.
"TARGET THEIR HEAD!"
"This won't be easy!"
Thassalin breathed out, then made a circle to get closer to the mountain that he called his home. The black beast followed, a bit frantic when a flash of fire hit her from behind. The creature hadn't noticed it wasn't alone anymore. Its panic grew when Thassalin slowed down, then hit it violently with his tail, making it deviate from its trajectory.
The creature, growling and whistling, took altitude and spat into the air. Suddenly, everything became black, as if the monster was sucking in the light from the sky and replacing it with a perpetual cloud of night.
Losing all visibility, Thassalin tried to retreat, but skimmed the tops of the trees before crashing into the clearing. As if she had known exactly where he had fallen, the creature charged straight for him, bringing the dark cloud in its wake.
"Kayel!", exclaimed Tenuk as he extricated himself from the cloud and began to fly in circles to try to locate Nyssi and Thassalin below, in the darkness. "What's going on, Kayel? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Down below, Nyssi struggled to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her unnatural healing powers had already begun to take effect. You couldn't say the same for Thassalin, who was lying on a mound, leaning against the only tree that hadn't bent under his weight. Nyssi did her best to try to reach Thassalin, but she couldn't see two meters in front of her. Everything was plunged into darkness, swallowed up in impious shadows. And in those shadows, something was screaming.
A horrible club-like tail came crashing down beside Nyssi, sending her tumbling over. However, she noted that the tail was moving, without aiming at her. The creature, from what Nyssi could see and hear, growled and scratched at the shadows it had created. Something was teleporting through the darkness, striking the monster, disorienting it.
Gunfire suddenly echoed, and the monster collapsed in silence, inanimate. The darkness surrounding them dissipated, revealing what had just passed. Standing on the creature was Kayel, gun in hand and short of breath.
"That's... the weirdest shadow jump I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kayel gasped. His eyes shone with a black glow, and a dark energy traversed his body. However, as he spoke, Kayel's organic plating regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow color.
It took Nyssi a moment to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel was gifted with strange shadow powers. He rarely used them, as most people considered them to be impious and rather terrifying. But Nyssi did not know that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And, judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed quite surprised himself.
"You're okay?", Nyssi could not help but ask.
"Yes, I'm fine. I killed something. It will be better in a minute." Kayel examined his work, as Tenuk made his way to land next to him, regaining his normal form of Spast.
Now that the creature wasn't moving anymore, they could see what it was better. Its skin was black as coal and sticky, but the slobber kept adhering to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all of which ended in long claws, and two straight horns protruded from its head.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what that thing was, something screamed and launched itself from a nearby bush. However, the beast didn't have time to reach them, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, throwing it at Nyssi's feet. Not taking any risks, the latter grabbed her rifle and shot it in the skull right away, killing the creature instantly.
"Oops...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before awkwardly cutting off the engine and jumping out of the truck. "I, uh, didn't mean to do that. Are you okay?"
"You practically missed the whole action," regretted Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"You all left me behind. I came here as fast as I could," sighed Retvik. "Can someone tell me what these wretched things are?"
L'interrogation de Retvik received a welcome response from Thassalin, who had just gotten up. He was badly cut and scratched all over and seemed a bit disoriented, but he didn't seem to be too hurt.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. THE CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN CORRUPTION ATE AT YOUR GODS."
"You mean... the horrible god monster that we helped kill?", stammered Tenuk.
"YES. ALL THE SAME. THERE MAY BE OTHERS, BUT I DIDN'T MANAGE TO HIT THEM ON THE HEAD. I LACK A RIFLE. PLUS, TWO AGAINST ONE ISN'T FAIR, IS IT?" Thassalin walked towards Kayel and patted him on the head. "THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. BUT LESS MURDERER AND LESS ABLE TO KILL UNIVERSES."
"Uh... thanks... I suppose", said Kayel with a shrug. "So, we're done here?"
Nissy raised her shoulders, then took her camera to photograph the now well-dead beasts. She then pulled out her favorite dagger, the god of death's, and began to cut one of the creature's horns, before attacking the other. But just as she finished, the creatures ignited and quickly turned into piles of ashes. The same thing happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut.
"Well... it's both convenient and not at all convenient", she sighed. "At least, I'm left with the photos..."
